itics found English composition - with the exception of Elgar - severely lacking. The book identifies themes such as materialism and nationalism that emerged during the debate. It also places the narrative of 'The English Musical Renaissance' within its rightful wider historical context.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aMusicxHistory and criticismy19th centuryzGreat Britain. 0aMusiczGreat Britainy19th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aMusical criticismxHistoryy19th centuryzGreat Britain. 4aMusic. 7aMUSIC / History & Criticism.2bisacsh  aDebating English Music.  aEnglish Musical Renaissance.  aHistorical Context.  aLong Nineteenth Century.  aMaterialism.  aMusic Criticism.  aMusic History.  aMusical Debate.  aMusical Identity.  aMusical Influence.  aNationalism.  aRichard Wagner.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311143100040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781800101500?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781800101500423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781800101500/original  a978-3-11-143100-0  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2021b2021  aGBV-deGruyter-alles